Kumar made his first appearance as the lead actor opposite [[Raakhee]] and [[Shantipriya (actress)|Shantipriya]] in ''[[Saugandh (1991 film)|Saugandh]]'' (1991). In the same year, he acted in Kishore Vyas-directed ''[[Dancer (1991 film)|Dancer]]'', which received poor reviews.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Verma|first1=Sukanya|title=The Ten Worst Films of Akshay Kumar (Dancer)|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-worst-of-akshay-kumar/20111128.htm#1|accessdate=8 November 2014|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|date=28 November 2011|location=Mumbai}}</ref> The following year he starred in [[Abbas Mustan]]-directed suspense thriller, ''[[Khiladi (1992 film)|Khiladi]]'', widely considered his [[breakthrough role]].<ref name="FP786">{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/movie-review-khiladi-786-is-a-leave-your-brains-at-home-kinda-comedy-550305.html |title=Movie review: Khiladi 786 is a leave-your-brains-at-home kinda comedy|work=[[Firstpost]]|publisher=[[Network 18]]|date=8 December 2012|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Akshay Kumar- The Khiladi superstar|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/slideshow/akshay-kumar-the-khiladi-star_203.html|publisher=[[Zee News]]|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref><ref name="KSeries">{{cite web|last1=Basu|first1=Mohar|title=Khel Khiladi Ka – Akshay Kumar Strikes Back with Khiladi 786|url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/khel-khiladi-ka-akshay-kumar-strikes-back-with-khiladi-786/|publisher=[[Koimoi]]|accessdate=4 October 2014|date=3 November 2012}}</ref> His next release was the [[Raj Sippy]]-directed detective film ''[[Mr. Bond]]'', based on [[James Bond]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bombay Bond – Akshay Kumar to play lead in Raj Sippy's film Mr Bond|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/akshay-kumar-to-play-lead-in-raj-sippy-film-mr-bond/1/318818.html|accessdate=8 November 2014|work=[[India Today]]|date=30 September 1991}}</ref> His last release of 1992 was ''[[Deedar (1992 film)|Deedar]]''. It failed to perform well at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Srinivasan|first1=V S|title=Akki up front|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/aug/10akki.htm|accessdate=8 November 2014|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|date=11 August 1998}}</ref> In 1993, he acted in the [[Keshu Ramsay]]-directed bilingual film  ''[[Ashaant]]'' (released in [[Kannada language|Kannada]] as ''Vishnu-Vijaya'') and starring [[Vishnuvardhan (actor)|Dr. Vishnuvardhan]], [[Ashwini Bhave]] and [[Ashutosh Rana]]. All of his films released during 1993, including ''[[Dil Ki Baazi]]'', ''[[Kayda Kanoon]]'', ''[[Waqt Hamara Hai]]'' and ''[[Sainik]]'' did not perform well commercially.<ref name="Slide6" /> In 1994, he played a police inspector in two films: Sameer Malkan-directed remake of Hollywood film ''[[The Hard Way (1991 film)|The Hard Way]]'', ''[[Main Khiladi Tu Anari]]'' and [[Rajiv Rai]]-directed ''[[Mohra]]'' which were among the highest-grossing films of the year.<ref name="1994 BO">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=200&catName=MTk5NA== |title=Box Office 1994 |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404040854/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=200&catName=MTk5NA%3D%3D&PHPSESSID=dfc0170bd04e78fc807ed337537b9c9f |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Later that year, he starred in [[Yash Chopra]]-produced romance, ''[[Yeh Dillagi]]'' opposite [[Kajol]]. His role in the film earned Kumar his first nomination for [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor at the Filmfare Awards]]<ref>{{cite news|title=The nominations-1994|url=http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/articleshow/368622.cms|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130103094834/http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/articleshow/368622.cms|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 January 2013|work=[[Times Internet|The Times of India]]|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> and [[Star Screen Awards|Star Screen]] award.<ref name="Slide6">{{cite web|title=Akshay Kumar, the Entertainment Khiladi, Turns 47 (Slide 6)|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/photos/akshay-kumar-the-entertainment-khiladi-turns-47-15948/slide/6|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> During the same year, Kumar also had success with films like ''[[Suhaag (1994 film)|Suhaag]]'' and the low budget action film ''[[Elaan (1994 film)|Elaan]]''. All these achievements, promoted Kumar as one of the most successful actors of the year.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Box Office India|title=Top Actor|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=top_actors|accessdate=14 March 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080323030211/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=top_actors&PHPSESSID=7ad4adadd9d256d7d66d404f22e56d40| archivedate= 23 March 2008 | url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1994, he appeared in 11 feature films.<ref name="maxmrelease">{{cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrities/features/type/view/id/4327|title=After 20 years, Akshay to set new record with Special Chabbis|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=22 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203064510/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrities/features/type/view/id/4327|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref>

The following year, Kumar played [[dual role]] in [[Umesh Mehra]]-directed [[action thriller]], ''[[Sabse Bada Khiladi]]'', which was a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Box Office 1995 |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=201&catName=MTk5NQ== |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |accessdate=11 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404040900/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=201&catName=MTk5NQ%3D%3D&PHPSESSID=dfc0170bd04e78fc807ed337537b9c9f |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He proved to have success with the ''Khiladi'' series, as in the next year he starred in the fourth film of the ''Khiladi'' series, ''[[Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi]]'' opposite [[Rekha]] and [[Raveena Tandon]]. The film was a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=202&catName=MTk5Ng== |title=Box Office 1996 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404040905/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=202&catName=MTk5Ng%3D%3D&PHPSESSID=dfc0170bd04e78fc807ed337537b9c9f |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the film's shooting Kumar was injured. He received treatment in United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Akshay Kumar, the Entertainment Khiladi, Turns 47 (Slide 8)|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/photos/akshay-kumar-the-entertainment-khiladi-turns-47-15948/slide/8|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> Shubhra Gupta of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' wrote in a year-end review, "It was Akshay Kumar in ''Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi'' who packed the aisles, no doubt about it... He shoved his hair back in a slick little ponytail, much like [[Steven Segal]], wore ankle-length great coats, wrestled with the fearsome [[Undertaker]], and walked away with the film."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gupta |first1=Shubhra |title=Formula Fatigue |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970424094007/http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19961006/28050762.html |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=The Indian Express |date=24 April 1997}}</ref>

Kumar played a supporting role in [[Yash Chopra]]-directed romance, ''[[Dil To Pagal Hai]]'' (1997), co-starring [[Shah Rukh Khan]], [[Madhuri Dixit]] and [[Karisma Kapoor]], for which he received his first nomination for the [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actor Award]].<ref name="FFD">{{cite news|title=The Nominations – 1997|url=http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/articleshow/368659.cms|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709173248/http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/articleshow/368659.cms|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2012|work=[[Times Internet|The Times of India]]|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref> In the same year, he starred opposite [[Juhi Chawla]] in [[David Dhawan]]-directed comedy ''[[Mr. and Mrs. Khiladi]]'', fifth instalment of the ''Khiladi'' series. Unlike his previous films of the series, it failed commercially.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=203&catName=MTk5Nw== |title=Box Office 1997 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404040910/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=203&catName=MTk5Nw%3D%3D&PHPSESSID=dfc0170bd04e78fc807ed337537b9c9f |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Considerable success, however, came with another dual role in the romantic action film ''[[Aflatoon (film)|Aflatoon]]''. Critic [[Khalid Mohamed]], while critical of the film, approved of Kumar's effort: "Akshay Kumar comes to life. Given something even slightly different to do, he does rise to the occasion."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohamed |first1=Khalid|title=Hiss Story|url=http://www.filmfare.com/site/btalkies/bomb2.htm |work=Filmfare |publisher=Times Group |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991001170900/http://www.filmfare.com/site/btalkies/bomb2.htm|archivedate=1 October 1999}}</ref>His following releases failed commercial and this caused a setback to his film career.<ref>{{cite news|title=I started my career with B-grade films: Akshay Kumar|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2012/akshay-kumar-b-grade-films-096240.html|publisher=[[Oneindia.in]]|accessdate=17 June 2014|date=5 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715043640/http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2012/akshay-kumar-b-grade-films-096240.html|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref> In 1999, Kumar played opposite [[Twinkle Khanna]] in ''International Khiladi''. The film turned out to be an average grosser at the box office.<ref name="KSeries" /> He received critical acclaim for his roles in the films ''[[Sangharsh (1999 film)|Sangharsh]]'' and ''[[Jaanwar (1999 film)|Jaanwar]]''. Whilst the former did not make a profit at the box office, the latter turned out to be a commercial success and marked his comeback.<ref name="akki">{{cite web|title=Akshay Kumar|url=http://www.koimoi.com/actor/akshay-kumar/|publisher=[[Koimoi]]|accessdate=17 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140211095734/http://www.koimoi.com/actor/akshay-kumar/| archivedate=11 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/happy-birthday-akshay-kumar-bollywoods-khiladi-turns-46/#b_id_417845_akshaysangharshjanwar|title=Happy Birthday Akshay Kumar: Bollywood's Khiladi turns 46|work=[[The Indian Express]]|publisher=[[Indian Express Group]]|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=205&catName=MTk5OQ== |title=Box Office 1999 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404040915/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=205&catName=MTk5OQ%3D%3D&PHPSESSID=dfc0170bd04e78fc807ed337537b9c9f |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

=== 2000–06 ===

In 2000, Kumar starred in the [[Priyadarshan]]-directed comedy ''[[Hera Pheri (2000 film)|Hera Pheri]]'' alongside [[Paresh Rawal]] and [[Sunil Shetty]]. The film which was a remake of Malayalam film ''[[Ramji Rao Speaking]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Siddique's not teaming up with Priyadarshan for Hera Pheri 3|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news-and-interviews/Siddiques-not-teaming-up-with-Priyadarshan-for-Hera-Pheri-3/articleshow/18046718.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=17 January 2013}}</ref> became a commercial success<ref name="2000 BO">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=206&catName=MjAwMA== |title=Box Office 2000 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080323090246/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=206&catName=MjAwMA%3D%3D |archivedate=23 March 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and proved to be a turning point in Kumar's career.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jha|first1=Subhash K.|title=Akshay Kumar teams up with Priyadarshan again|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2508177/Akshay-Kumar-teams-up-with-Priyadarshan-again|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=23 May 2014}}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' noted the film's "intense portrayal of the surreality of the human condition".<ref>{{cite news|author=Kumar Choudhury, Arnab|date=2000|url=http://www.go4i.com/cinema/reviews/bollywood/reviewsbollywoodhp.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010609181551/http://www.go4i.com/cinema/reviews/bollywood/reviewsbollywoodhp.shtml|url-status=dead|archivedate=9 June 2001|accessdate=19 April 2020|title=Hera Pheri|newspaper=Hindustan Times}}</ref> He also starred in the [[Dharmesh Darshan]]-directed romantic drama ''[[Dhadkan]]'' later that same year. The film performed moderately at the box office<ref name="2000 BO" /> but Kumar was praised for his acting.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nair|first1=Padmaraj |title=The good ol’ 60s revisited|url=http://www.screenindia.com/20000818/freview.htm#dha|accessdate=19 April 2020|work=Screen |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021007002208/http://www.screenindia.com/20000818/freview.htm#dha|date=18 August 2000|archivedate=7 December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Raheja |first1=Dinesh |authorlink1=Dinesh Raheja |title=Dhadkan — Misses a beat |url=http://movies.india-today.com/reviews/reviewdhadkan.shtml |accessdate=9 May 2020 |work=India Today |date=2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010222060827/http://movies.india-today.com/reviews/reviewdhadkan.shtml |archivedate=22 February 2001}}</ref> [[Rediff.com]]'s review stated that he had proved that he is "director's actor" and that "he has worked hard on his role is apparent."<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dhadkan review|url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2000/aug/11dhad.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> That same year, he performed some of his most dangerous stunts in Neeraj Vora-directed action thriller ''[[Khiladi 420]]'', where he climbed a running plane, stood on top of the plane flying a thousand feet in the air, and jumped from the plane onto a hot air balloon. In a later scene, he is also seen being chased by a car, dodging bullets, jumping off buildings, and climbing walls.<ref>{{cite news|title=Akshay Kumar's Top 5 Stunts|publisher=[[DesiHits]]|url=http://www.desihits.com/news/view/akshay-kumar-s-top-5-stunts-20100616|accessdate=11 April 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230148/http://www.desihits.com/news/view/akshay-kumar-s-top-5-stunts-20100616|archivedate=2 December 2013}}</ref> His character in the film had two names and his role received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Movie review: Khiladi 420|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/201884|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=30 December 2000}}</ref> Sukanya Verma wrote "Negative roles and Akshay Kumar don't go hand-in-hand. [...] Akshay is ridiculously over the top and irritating to the core. However, he manages a decent performance as the sober and suave Anand."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Verma|first1=Sukanya|title=Action?Thriller |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/dec/29khil.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=29 December 2000}}</ref> Padmaraj Nair of ''[[Screen India|Screen]]'', however, believed it was "the best performance of his career".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nair|first1=Padmaraj |title=Desi version of Surrogate Mother|url=http://www.screenindia.com/20010112/review.htm|accessdate=19 April 2020|work=Screen |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021206160451/http://www.screenindia.com/20010112/review.htm|date=12 January 2001|archivedate=6 December 2002}}</ref>

His first release in 2001 was [[Suneel Darshan]]-directed drama ''[[Ek Rishtaa: The Bond of Love]]''. Kumar was praised for his performance in the film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Someshwar|first1=Savera R|title=Movie review: Ek Rishtaa: The Bond of Love|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2001/may/18rish.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=18 May 2001}}</ref> Next, he played a negative role in the Abbas Mustan-directed film ''[[Ajnabee (2001 film)|Ajnabee]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/bollywood/news/a572942/akshay-kumar-i-want-to-do-more-villain-roles.html|title=Akshay Kumar: 'I want to do more villain roles'|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=23 May 2014|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Happy Birthday Akshay Kumar: Bollywood's Khiladi turns 46|url=http://indianexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/happy-birthday-akshay-kumar-bollywoods-khiladi-turns-46/#b_id_417843_akshayaankheinajnabee|work=[[The Indian Express]]|publisher=[[Indian Express Group]]|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> While reviewing the film for Rediff.com, Sarita Tanwar termed Kumar the "surprise package" of the film. She added that he was "in total control as the bad guy."<ref>{{cite web|last=Tanwar|first=Sarita|title=The Rediff Review: Ajnabee|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2001/sep/20ajna.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=23 August 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417233043/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2001/sep/20ajna.htm|archivedate=17 April 2009}}</ref> The film won him critical acclaim as well as his first Filmfare Award for [[Filmfare Best Villain Award|Best Villain]] and IIFA award 2002 for Performance in a Negative Role.<ref name="25years" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iifa.com/city_malaysia.php|title=IIFA 2002|accessdate=21 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528050050/http://www.iifa.com/city_malaysia.php|archivedate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Winners – 2001 – The 51st Filmfare Awards|url=http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/368739.cms|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709023301/http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/368739.cms|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 July 2012|work=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref>

[[File:Akshay Kumar in Sydney for Heyy Babyy.jpg|left|thumb|Kumar on the set of ''[[Heyy Babyy]]'', 2007.]]

His first release in 2002 was [[Dharmesh Darshan]]-directed romantic drama ''[[Haan Maine Bhi Pyaar Kiya]]''. He played the role as a blind man in [[Vipul Amrutlal Shah]] and Shaarang Dev Pandit-directed [[heist film]] ''[[Aankhen (2002 film)|Aankhen]]'', co-starring [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Arjun Rampal]], [[Aditya Pancholi]], [[Sushmita Sen]] and [[Paresh Rawal]]. His performance in the film was critically acclaimed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aankhen|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/reviews/type/view/id/735/Aankhen|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=27 August 2014|date=5 April 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aankhen takes you on a roller-coaster ride|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/coventry/films/reviews/a_f/aankhen-review.shtml|publisher=BBC|accessdate=27 August 2014|date=12 April 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ganapati|first1=Priya|title=Movie review: Aankhen|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/apr/05aank.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=5 April 2002}}</ref> Next, he starred in the [[Vikram Bhatt]]-directed comedy ''[[Awara Paagal Deewana]]''. Rediff.com's review of the film mentioned that his sincerity and intensity seen in ''Hera Pheri'', ''Ek Rishtaa – The Bond of Love'' and ''Aankhen'' "seems missing".<ref>{{cite web|author=Anjum, N|title=Akshay, Sunil, Aftab's star power fails, Paresh Rawal steals the show|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2002/jun/21apd.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=21 June 2002}}</ref> His last film of the year was [[Rajkumar Kohli]]-directed [[supernatural horror film]]'' [[Jaani Dushman: Ek Anokhi Kahani]]'' alongside [[Manisha Koirala]], Sunil Shetty, [[Sunny Deol]], [[Aftab Shivdasani]], [[Arshad Warsi]], Aditya Pancholi and [[Armaan Kohli]]. The film was a remake of Kohli's former film ''Naagin'' and received mostly negative reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kulkarni|first1=Ronjita|title=Jaani Dushman – Ek Anokhi torture|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/aug/17jaani.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=17 August 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Movie Review: Jaani Dushman – Ek Anokhi Kahani|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/preview.php?ctid=5&cid=2425&id=11829641|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=28 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908073530/http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/preview.php?ctid=5&cid=2425&id=11829641|archive-date=8 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Taran Adarsh wrote "only Munish[Armaan] Kohli and Akshay Kumar leave an impact."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Movie review: Jaani Dushman|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/539470|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=16 August 2002}}</ref> In 2003 he starred in Suneel Darshan's action film ''[[Talaash: The Hunt Begins...]]'' opposite [[Kareena Kapoor]]. While reviewing the film, Taran Adarsh wrote "Akshay Kumar is plain mediocre. The role hardly offers him scope to try out anything different."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Movie review: Talaash... The Hunt Begins|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/reviews/type/view/id/923/Talaash...%20The%20Hunt%20Begins|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=3 January 2003}}</ref> Next, he starred in [[Raj Kanwar]]-directed romantic drama ''[[Andaaz]]'' alongside [[Priyanka Chopra]] and [[Lara Dutta]]. The film received mixed reviews from critics,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Magotra|first1=Ashish|title='Andaaz': Flight to boredom|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/may/23andaaz.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=24 May 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shah |first1=Kunal |title=Andaaz: Old story, fresh faces |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/andaaz-old-story-fresh-faces-review-bollywood-13157317.html |publisher=Sify |accessdate=30 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329142128/http://www.sify.com/movies/andaaz-old-story-fresh-faces-review-bollywood-13157317.html |archivedate=29 March 2014 }}</ref> but turned out to be a commercial success at the box office and the first universal hit of 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=Box Office 2003 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=209&catName=MjAwMw== |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=30 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121000737/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=209&catName=MjAwMw%3D%3D |archivedate=21 January 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title='Andaaz' Celebrations: Rocking|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/news/type/view/id/1192968|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=29 August 2003}}</ref>

In 2004 Kumar starred in [[Rajkumar Santoshi]]'s action drama thriller ''[[Khakee]]'' alongside [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Ajay Devgn]] and [[Aishwarya Rai]]. Kumar played the role of Inspector Shekhar Verma, a corrupt, morally bankrupt cop who changes himself during a mission to transfer an accused [[Inter-Services Intelligence|Pakistani spy]] Dr. Iqbal Ansari (played by [[Atul Kulkarni (actor born 1965)|Atul Kulkarni]]) from a remote town in [[Maharashtra]] to [[Mumbai]]. The film and Kumar's acting were positively reviewed by critics.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hindu : "Khakee"|url=http://www.thehindu.com/fr/2004/02/06/stories/2004020601230302.htm|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|publisher=[[The Hindu Group]]|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=6 February 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Verma|first1=Sukanya|title=Khakee is money's worth. What more do you want?|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/jan/23khakee.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=24 January 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Elley|first1=Derek|title=Review: 'Khakee'|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/khakee-1200536726/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=31 January 2014}}</ref> He was nominated for the Filmfare Best Supporting Actor Award for his role in the film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roy|first1=Deb|title=10 Best Action Movies of Akshay Kumar (Slide 1)|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/top-10s/20760-10-best-action-movies-of-akshay-kumar-p1.html|publisher=[[MensXP.com]]|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> His other releases included Dileep Shukla's crime film ''[[Police Force: An Inside Story]]''. He starred alongside Raveena Tandon, [[Amrish Puri]] and [[Raj Babbar]]. The film's production was delayed following the break-up of the lead actors Tandon and Kumar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Akki, Raveena join forces!|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/feb/13look.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=16 February 2004}}</ref> Upon release it received negative reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Movie review : Police Force|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/reviews/type/view/id/956/Police%20Force|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=28 May 2004}}</ref> Next, Kumar played Hari Om Patnaik, an [[Indian Police Services|IPS]] officer in [[Madhur Bhandarkar]]-directed ''[[Aan: Men at Work]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fernandes|first1=Vivek|title=Akshay: It's payback time!|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/may/27akshay.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=27 May 2004}}</ref> He starred in [[David Dhawan]]-directed romantic comedy ''[[Mujhse Shaadi Karogi]]'' alongside [[Salman Khan]] and [[Priyanka Chopra]]. He played the role of Sunny, Sameer (played by Khan)'s roommate who pursuits Rani (played by Chopra)-Sameer's love interest. The film received positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Verma|first1=Sukanya|title='Mujhse Shaadi Karogi' is another 'Main Hoon Na'|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/jul/30mujhse.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=30 July 2004}}</ref> Taran Adarsh praised Kumar and wrote "Akshay Kumar is a revelation [...] he surpasses his previous work. His timing is fantastic and the conviction with which he carries off the evil streak in his personality is bound to be talked-about in days to come."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Mujhse Shaadi Karogi|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/54557|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=28 July 2004}}</ref> His performance in the film earned him his third nomination for supporting actor at the [[Filmfare Awards]] as well as a nomination for [[Filmfare Award for Best Performance in a Comic Role|best comic role]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nominees of 50th Filmfare Awards- The 51st Filmfare Awards|url=http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1021384.cms|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120710013930/http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1021384.cms|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 July 2012|work=The Times of India|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> His other films included Abbas-Mustan directed ''[[Aitraaz]]'' and S M Iqbal's ''[[Meri Biwi Ka Jawaab Nahin]]''. In the former, Kumar [[Playing against type|played against type]] as a worker wrongly accused of [[sexual harassment]] by his female boss played by Chopra. According to the directors, ''Aitraaz'' was inspired by [[National Basketball Association]] player [[Kobe Bryant]] (who was accused of rape by a fan);<ref>{{cite web|title=Akshay Kumar plays a rapist! |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/Akshay-Kumar-plays-a-rapist-news-bollywood-kkfvKIjbegi.html |publisher=Sify |accessdate=30 August 2014 |date=13 July 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107054739/http://www.sify.com/movies/Akshay-Kumar-plays-a-rapist-news-bollywood-kkfvKIjbegi.html |archivedate=7 January 2016 }}</ref> and the film's development began when they read about [[kobe Bryant sexual assault case|his sexual-assault case]] in the newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Akshay has a lot of experience: Abbas-Mustan|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/interview.php?id=13606747&cid=2398|publisher=Sify|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=8 November 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107054739/http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/interview.php?id=13606747&cid=2398|archive-date=7 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Talking about the character Kumar said that it is realistic and could be described as a "new-age [[metrosexual]]" man. He added that ''Aitraaz'' was the boldest film he had done.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jha |first=Subhash K |title='Aitraaz' is my boldest film: Akshay Kumar |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/interview.php?id=13609029&cid=2398 |publisher=Sify |accessdate=30 August 2014 |date=12 November 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107054739/http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/interview.php?id=13609029&cid=2398 |archivedate=7 January 2016 }}</ref> In the latter he starred opposite [[Sridevi]]. The film was shot in 1994 but was released in 2004 after a delay of 10 years.

The next year Kumar starred in Dharmesh Darshan-directed [[romantic drama]] [[musical film]] ''[[Bewafaa (2005 film)|Bewafaa]]'' opposite Kareena Kapoor. He played the role of Raja, an aspiring musician who pursues his love interest Anjali (played by Kareena Kapoor) even after she is married to Aditya Sahai (played by [[Anil Kapoor]]). The film received mixed reviews from film critic but Kumar was praised for his acting. Anupama Chopra of India Today wrote that "Kareena Kapoor and Kumar stand out." Taran Adarsh wrote "Akshay Kumar does well in a role that fits him like a glove."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chopra|first1=Anupama|title=Old refashioned|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/film-review-bewafaa-starring-anil-kapoor-akshay-kumar-kareena-kapoor/1/194289.html|work=India Today|accessdate=7 September 2014|date=14 March 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Movie Review : Bewafaa|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/bewafaa-review-bollywood-13680719.html|publisher=Sify|accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref> Later that year he acted in Vipul Amrutlal Shah's family drama ''[[Waqt: The Race Against Time]]'' alongside Amitabh Bachchan, another Priyadarshan-directed comedy ''[[Garam Masala (2005 film)|Garam Masala]]'' alongside John Abraham. ''Waqt: The Race Against Time'' was a family drama film. The film and Kumar's acting received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pandohar|first1=Jaspreet|title=Waqt: The Race Against Time (2005)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2005/04/20/waqt_2005_review.shtml|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=14 April 2005| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091006152845/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2005/04/20/waqt_2005_review.shtml | archivedate=6 October 2009}}</ref> Vishal D'Souza wrote "Akshay shoulders an author-backed role, carrying more of the film's emotional baggage though he is distinctly uncomfortable in the soppy-weepy scenes."<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Souza|first1=Vishal|title=Waqt loses the race|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2005/apr/22waqt.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=30 August 2014|date=22 April 2005}}</ref> The films succeeded at the box office<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=210&catName=MjAwNA== |title=Box Office 2004 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404040700/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=210&catName=MjAwNA%3D%3D |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=211&catName=MjAwNQ== |title=Box Office 2005 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080404041634/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=211&catName=MjAwNQ%3D%3D |archivedate=4 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and his performance in the latter earned him his second Filmfare Award, for [[Filmfare Best Comedian Award|Best Comedian]].<ref name="25years" /> His other films included Vikram Bhatt-directed action comedy romance film ''[[Deewane Huye Paagal]]'' and Suneel Darshan directed [[romantic drama]] ''[[Dosti: Friends Forever]]''. In the former he starred alongside Shahid Kapoor, Sunil Shetty and [[Rimi Sen]] while in the latter he starred alongside Kareena Kapoor and Bobby Deol. Both of these films received positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last1=N|first1=Patcy|title=Deewane Hue Paagal: Good fun|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2005/nov/25dhp.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=7 September 2014|date=25 November 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Movie Review : Dosti – Friends Forever|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/review.php?id=14056806&ctid=5&cid=2425|publisher=Sify|accessdate=7 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912213501/http://www.sify.com/movies/review.php?id=14056806&ctid=5&cid=2425|archive-date=12 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Kumar's first release of 2006 was [[Rajkumar Santoshi]]-directed drama ''[[Family - Ties of Blood]]'' followed by Suneel Darshan's ''[[Mere Jeevan Saathi (2006 film)|Mere Jeevan Saathi]]'' and Raj Kanwar's ''[[Humko Deewana Kar Gaye]]''. Next, he starred in a sequel to ''Hera Pheri'' titled ''[[Phir Hera Pheri]]''. As was the former, the sequel became a huge success at the box office.<ref name="2006 BO">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=212&catName=MjAwNg== |title=Box Office 2006 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221095752/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=212&catName=MjAwNg%3D%3D |archivedate=21 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Later that year he starred alongside Salman Khan and [[Preity Zinta]] in the [[Shirish Kunder]]-directed romantic musical film ''[[Jaan-E-Mann]]''. The film was a well anticipated release, and despite receiving positive reviews from critics, did not do as well as expected at the box office.<ref name="2006 BO" /> The film received mostly negatively reviews. Vidya Pradhan of Rediff.com called it a "bizarre movie."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pradhan|first1=Vidya|title=Jaan-E-Mann is a bizarre movie|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/oct/23jaan.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=7 September 2014|date=23 October 2006}}</ref> Though the film under-performed, his role as a shy, lovable nerd was praised.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adarsh, Taran|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama|IndiaFM]]|title=Jaan-E-Mann Review|url=http://www.indiafm.com/movies/review/12573/index.html|date=20 October 2006|accessdate=14 April 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070403101903/http://indiafm.com/movies/review/12573/index.html| archivedate= 3 April 2007 | url-status=dead}}</ref> He ended the year with Priyadarshan's comedy murder mystery film ''[[Bhagam Bhag]]''. He starred alongside Lara Dutta, Govinda and Paresh Rawal and played the character of a theatre actor. The film received mixed reviews and Rediff.com called Kumar the real hero of the film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Singh|first1=Gullu|title=Bhagam Bhag: Akshay top, Govinda flop|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/dec/22bb.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=7 September 2014|date=22 December 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kazmi|first1=Nikhat|title=Bhagam Bhaag|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Bhagam-Bhaag/movie-review/903798.cms|work=The Times of India|accessdate=7 September 2014|date=22 December 2006}}</ref> The film was commercially successful.<ref name="2006 BO" /> The same year, he led the ''Heat 2006'' world tour along with fellow stars [[Saif Ali Khan]], [[Preity Zinta]], [[Sushmita Sen]] and [[Celina Jaitley]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Akshay Kumar & Preity Zinta in Bollywood New York Shows for Aron Govil Productions|date=10 March 2006|url=http://www.businesswireindia.com/PressRelease.asp?b2mid=9273|publisher=Business Wire India|accessdate=14 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060323185651/http://www.businesswireindia.com/PressRelease.asp?b2mid=9273|archivedate=23 March 2006}}</ref>

=== 2007–11 ===

[[File:Katrina Kaif and Akshay Kumar on the set of Namastey London.jpg|thumb|Akshay Kumar and Katrina Kaif on the set of ''Namastey London'']]

[[File:Akshay & Katrina on the sets of Welcome.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Kumar with [[Katrina Kaif]] on the sets of ''[[Welcome (2007 film)|Welcome]]'' (2007); the duo received appreciation for their pairing and appeared in several successful films together]]

2007 proved to be Kumar's most successful year during his career in the industry, and as described by box office analysts, "probably the best ever recorded by an actor, with four outright hits and no flops."<ref name="BO 2007">{{cite news|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=42&nCat=news|title=The Toppers of 2007|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=14 March 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115082127/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=42&nCat=news|archivedate=15 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=I am kind to everyone, but trust no one: Akshay Kumar|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-am-kind-to-everyone-but-trust-no-one-Akshay-Kumar/articleshow/9779766.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=21 August 2014|date=29 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mishra|first1=Somen|title=Akshay Kumar crowned 2007 King of Bollywood|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/akshay-kumar-crowned-2007-king-of-bollywood/55446-8.html|accessdate=6 November 2014|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|date=2 January 2008|location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Singh|first1=Mauli|last2=Shah|first2=Jigar|title=Khiladi is King|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/khiladi-is-king/article3023231.ece|accessdate=6 November 2014|work=[[The Hindu]]|publisher=[[The Hindu Group]]|date=15 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Akshay- the undisputed king of Bollywood, bags Rs 72 crore deal|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/akshay-the-undisputed-king-of-bollywood-bags-rs72-crore-deal_8541.html|accessdate=6 November 2014|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=22 August 2008|location=Mumbai}}</ref> His first release, [[Vipul Amrutlal Shah]]-directed ''[[Namastey London]]'', was critically and commercially successful, and his performance earned him a Best Actor nomination at the Filmfare. Critic [[Taran Adarsh]] wrote of his performance in the film, "he's sure to win the hearts of millions of moviegoers with a terrific portrayal in this film."<ref>{{cite news|author=Adarsh, Taran|url=http://indiafm.com/movies/review/12835/index.html|title=Review of Namastey London|date=23 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2007|publisher=IndiaFM| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070405202710/http://www.indiafm.com/movies/review/12835/index.html| archivedate= 5 April 2007}}</ref> Kumar's chemistry with lead actress Katrina Kaif also generated immense appreciation, with [[Nikhat Kazmi]] of ''[[The Times of India]]'' describing their pairing as "refreshing."<ref>{{cite news|last=Kazmi|first=Nikhat|title=Namastey London|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/hindi/Namastey-London/movie-review/1802925.cms|accessdate=21 August 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|date=24 March 2007}}</ref> His next two releases, [[Sajid Khan]]-directed ''[[Heyy Babyy]]'' and Priyadarshan's ''[[Bhool Bhulaiyaa]]'', were box office successes as well.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adarsh, Taran|title=Top 5: 'Dhamaal' average, 'Darling' slumps!|url=http://www.indiafm.com/trade/top5/380.html|date=15 September 2007|accessdate=14 March 2008|publisher=IndiaFM|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015033244/http://indiafm.com/trade/top5/380.html|archivedate=15 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Adarsh, Taran|title=Top 5: 'J.W.M.' steady, despite pre-Diwali dull phase|url=http://www.indiafm.com/trade/top5/396.html|date=10 November 2007|publisher=IndiaFM|accessdate=10 November 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071115221205/http://www.indiafm.com/trade/top5/396.html| archivedate= 15 November 2007}}</ref> In both of these films he starred opposite [[Vidya Balan]]. Kumar's last release of the year, the [[Anees Bazmee]]-directed ''[[Welcome (2007 film)|Welcome]]'', did extremely well at the box office, receiving a blockbuster status and simultaneously becoming his fifth successive hit.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=IndiaFM|author=Adarsh, Taran|title=Midweek: 'Welcome', 'TZP' continue to rock!|url=http://www.indiafm.com/trade/top5/411.html|date=1 January 2008|accessdate=1 January 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080108131929/http://www.indiafm.com/trade/top5/411.html| archivedate= 8 January 2008}}</ref> All of Kumar's films which released that year did well in the overseas market as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=overseas_earners|title=Overseas Earnings (Figures in Ind Rs)|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=14 March 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080317191849/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=overseas_earners&PHPSESSID=b754628e151e869b2426dfd035eb7581| archivedate= 17 March 2008}}</ref> Kumar appeared in a cameo role in [[Farah Khan]] directed ''[[Om Shanti Om]]''. His role was listed as no. 3 on the Top 10 Cameos in Bollywood list of [[MensXP.com]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saikia|first1=Priyankee|title=Top 10 Cameos in Bollywood|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/bollywood/9378-top-10-cameos-in-bollywood.html|publisher=[[MensXP.com]]|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref>

Kumar's first film of 2008, [[Vijay Krishna Acharya]]-directed action thriller ''[[Tashan (film)|Tashan]]'', marked his comeback to the [[Yash Raj Films]] banner after 11 years. Although a poll (conducted by Bollywood Hungama) named it the most anticipated release of the year,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://oldbh.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2008/02/08/3550/index.html|title=The Most Awaited movies of 2008|accessdate=19 May 2009|author=Bollywood Hungama News Network|date=8 February 2008|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126145213/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2008/02/08/3550/index.html|archivedate=26 January 2009}}</ref> the film under-performed at the box office grossing {{INRConvert|279|m}} in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=215&catName=MjAwOA== |title=Box Office 2008 |accessdate=20 January 2009 |publisher=Box Office India |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012165321/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=215&catName=MjAwOA%3D%3D |archivedate=12 October 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His second film, Bazmee-directed ''[[Singh Is Kinng]]'' in which he starred opposite Kaif was a huge success at the box office and broke the first-week worldwide record of ''[[Om Shanti Om (film)|Om Shanti Om]]'', the previous highest figure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=215&catName=MjAwOA== |title=Box Office 2008 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=28 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115083431/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=215&catName=MjAwOA%3D%3D |archivedate=15 January 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His next film was the animated film ''[[Jumbo (film)|Jumbo]]'', directed by Kompin Kemgumnird. The year also saw Kumar making his small screen debut as the host of the successful show ''[[Fear Factor&nbsp;– Khatron Ke Khiladi]]''. He later returned to host the show's [[Fear Factor&nbsp;– Khatron Ke Khiladi Level 2|second season]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Khanna|first1=Niyati|title=Tracing The Journey of Fear Factor – Khatron Ke Khiladi; Season 5 Back with a Bang|url=http://businessofcinema.com/tele/tracing-journey-fear-factor-khatron-ke-khiladi-season-5-back-bang/131637|work=Business of Cinema|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=31 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Priyanka Chopra to host 'Fear Factor, Season 3'|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/television/article202006.ece|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|publisher=Express Publications|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=8 August 2010}}</ref>

In 2009, Kumar featured opposite [[Deepika Padukone]] in the [[Warner Bros.]] and [[Rohan Sippy]] production ''[[Chandni Chowk to China]]''. Directed by [[Nikhil Advani]], the film was a critical and commercial failure at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kazmi|first1=Nikhat|title=Chandni Chowk to China|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Chandni-Chowk-to-China/movie-review/3985572.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=15 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sen|first1=Raja|title=Hindi Chini Why Why?|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/jan/16review-chandni-chowk-to-china.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=16 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=791&nCat=news|title=Ten Releases Five Disasters|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=5 March 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213174227/http://boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=791&nCat=news|archivedate=13 February 2009}}</ref> Kumar's next release was ''[[8 x 10 Tasveer]]'', an action-thriller directed by [[Nagesh Kukunoor]] that failed commercially. His next release was [[Sabbir Khan]]'s [[wikt:battle of the sexes|battle-of-the-sexes]] comedy ''[[Kambakkht Ishq]]''. Set in Los Angeles, it was the first Indian film to be shot at [[Universal Studios Hollywood|Universal Studios]] and featured cameo appearances by Hollywood actors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/news-feed/archived-stories/nadiadwala-takes-akshay-kumar-to-hollywood/article1-282116.aspx |title=Nadiadwala takes Akshay Kumar to Hollywood |accessdate=27 May 2012 |agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service]] |date=14 March 2008 |work=[[Hindustan Times]]  |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023121936/http://www.hindustantimes.com/news-feed/archived-stories/nadiadwala-takes-akshay-kumar-to-hollywood/article1-282116.aspx |archivedate=23 October 2013 }}</ref> The film was poorly received by critics but became an economic success, earning over {{INRConvert|840|m}} worldwide. Kumar's film ''[[Blue (2009 film)|Blue]]'' was released on 16 October 2009. ''[[Blue (2009 film)|Blue]]'' received negative reviews and collected about ₹ 420&nbsp;million at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pal|first1=Chandrima|title=Blue: Blistering Barnacles!|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/movie-review-blue/20091016.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|location=Mumbai|date=16 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chopra|first1=Anupama|title=Blue|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/blue-442|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=16 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chopra|first1=Sonia|title=Review: Blue is a damp squib|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/review-blue-is-a-damp-squib-review-bollywood-14915122.html|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> His last release in 2009 was Priyadarshan's ''[[De Dana Dan]]''. He starred alongside Katrina Kaif, Suniel Shetty and Paresh Rawal. Kumar played a servant who plans to kidnap his owner's dog. The film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=De Dana Dan|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/502796|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=27 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chopra|first1=Anupama|title=De Dana Dan|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/de-dana-dan-458|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=27 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kazmi|first1=Nikhat|title=De Dana Dan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/De-Dana-Dan/movie-review/5272173.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=26 November 2009}}</ref>

He then appeared in the 2010 comedy, ''[[Housefull (2010 film)|Housefull]]'', directed by [[Sajid Khan]] which garnered the second-highest opening weekend collection of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://movies.rediff.com/report/2010/may/03/housefull-gets-biggest-opening-since-3-idiots.htm |title= Housefull gets biggest opening since 3 Idiots |author= Vinod Marani |date= 3 May 2010|publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |accessdate=17 May 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100516143917/http://movies.rediff.com/report/2010/may/03/housefull-gets-biggest-opening-since-3-idiots.htm| archivedate= 16 May 2010}}</ref> Kumar's next release was ''[[Khatta Meetha (2010 film)|Khatta Meetha]]'', directed by [[Priyadarshan]] which was an average grosser. The film received negative reviews.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adarsh|first1=Taran|title=Khatta Meetha|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/khatta-meetha-review-this-satire-is-far-from-meetha-review-bollywood-14950664.html|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Rajeev Masand of CNN-IBN called it a schizophrenic film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Masand|first1=Rajeev|title=Masand: 'Khatta Meetha', a schizophrenic film|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-khatta-meetha-a-schizophrenic-film/127366-47.html|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=31 July 2010}}</ref>
He also appeared in [[Vipul Shah]]'s ''[[Action Replayy]]'', which was a box office failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2201&nCat=box_office_news%E2%80%9D |title=Boxofficeindia.com |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |date=8 November 2010 |accessdate=9 June 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120329011947/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2201&nCat=box_office_news%E2%80%9D|archivedate=29 March 2012}}</ref> The film received mostly negative reviews.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kazmi|first1=Nikhat|title=Action Replayy|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Action-Replayy/movie-review/6871125.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=4 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shekhar |first1=Mayank |title=Mayank Shekhar's review: Action Replayy |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/reviews/mayank-shekhar-s-review-action-replayy/article1-622338.aspx |work=[[Hindustan Times]]  |accessdate=8 September 2014 |date=4 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116144133/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/reviews/mayank-shekhar-s-review-action-replayy/article1-622338.aspx |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> His last film of 2010 was ''[[Tees Maar Khan (2010 film)|Tees Maar Khan]]''. Directed by [[Farah Khan]], the film received poor critical reviews and turned out to be a commercial failure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rao|first1=Renuka|title=Review: Tees Maar Khan is not worth even a free ticket|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review-review-tees-maar-khan-is-not-worth-even-a-free-ticket-1485367|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|publisher=Diligent Media Corporation|accessdate=8 September 2014|location=Mumbai|date=23 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kazmi|first1=Nikhat|title=Tees Maar Khan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Tees-Maar-Khan/movie-review/7149954.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=23 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/akshay-kumar-will-woo-katrina-kaif-on-screen-for-the-seventh-time-317005|title=Akshay Kumar will woo Katrina Kaif on-screen for the seventh time|date=14 January 2013|publisher= [[NDTV]] |accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref>

In 2011 he starred in ''[[Patiala House (film)|Patiala House]]'' and ''[[Thank You (2011 film)|Thank You]]''. His last film of 2011 was Rohit Dhawan-directed ''[[Desi Boyz]]'' (2011), which co-starred [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]], [[Chitrangada Singh]] and [[Deepika Padukone]]. He also co-produced a film with [[Russell Peters]] titled ''[[Breakaway (2011 film)|Breakaway]]'' (dubbed into Hindi as [[Speedy Singhs]]) which is reminiscent of his own ''Patiala House''.<ref name="break">{{cite news|url=http://www.sawfnews.com/Bollywood/67040.aspx |title=Akshay Kumar, Russell Peters' Breakaway Gets Media Attention |publisher=Sawfnews.com |date= 6 June 2011|accessdate=9 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608185615/http://www.sawfnews.com/Bollywood/67040.aspx|archivedate=8 June 2011}}</ref> ''Breakaway'' became the highest-grossing cross-cultural movie of 2011 in Canada. Kumar dubbed for the role of Optimus Prime in the Hindi version of Hollywood, action blockbuster, ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]''. He took the dubbing role for his son, Aarav, and did so for free.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dubaichronicle.com/2011/07/29/bollywood-superstar-akshay-kumar-superhero-for-his-son/ |title=Bollywood Superstar, Akshay Kumar Superhero for his Son |work=Dubai Chronicle |accessdate=29 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001073104/http://www.dubaichronicle.com/2011/07/29/bollywood-superstar-akshay-kumar-superhero-for-his-son/|archivedate=1 October 2011}}</ref>

=== 2012–15 ===
